03712nam a22005655i 9781478005650DE-B159720200928045905.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200928t20192019ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019010888  a97814780056507 a10.1515/97814780056502doi  a(DE-B1597)552903  a(OCoLC)1138560655  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aGN670b.A785 2019 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a305.8969/42231 aArvin, Maile Renee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPossessing Polynesians :bThe Science of Settler Colonial Whiteness in Hawai`i and Oceania /cMaile Renee Arvin. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b19 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Polynesia Is a Project, Not a Place -- tPart I. The Polynesian Problem. Scientific Production of the "Almost White" Polynesian Race -- tPart II. Regenerative Refusals. Confronting Contemporary Legacies of the Polynesian Problem in Hawaiʻi and Oceania -- tConclusion. Regenerating an Oceanic Future in Indigenous Space-Time -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom their earliest encounters with Indigenous Pacific Islanders, white Europeans and Americans asserted an identification with the racial origins of Polynesians, declaring them to be racially almost white and speculating that they were of Mediterranean or Aryan descent. In Possessing Polynesians Maile Arvin analyzes this racializing history within the context of settler colonialism across Polynesia, especially in Hawai'i. Arvin argues that a logic of possession through whiteness animates settler colonialism, by which both Polynesia (the place) and Polynesians (the people) become exotic, feminized belongings of whiteness. Seeing whiteness as indigenous to Polynesia provided white settlers with the justification needed to claim Polynesian lands and resources. Understood as possessions, Polynesians were and continue to be denied the privileges of whiteness. Yet Polynesians have long contested these classifications, claims, and cultural representations, and Arvin shows how their resistance to and refusal of white settler logic have regenerated Indigenous forms of recognition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aEthnologyzPolynesia. 0aPolynesiansxOrigin. 0aPolynesiansxRace identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005650zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005650423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005650.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles